<h1 class="hero-h">Claude + <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">HubSpot integration.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">HubSpot has its own AI features baked in, but they cover maybe 30% of what a serious GTM team needs Claude for. Here's how to use Claude alongside HubSpot effectively — from simple manual workflows to custom integrations, plus when to stick with HubSpot AI and when to leave the platform for Claude.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The integration paths</span><h2 class="h2">Four ways to get Claude working with HubSpot data</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>1. Manual copy-paste.</strong> Rep pulls contact/company/deal info from HubSpot into Claude. Zero setup. Adequate for small teams. Friction adds up at scale.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>2. HubSpot reports → Claude Project knowledge base.</strong> Weekly contact, deal, or workflow exports loaded into a dedicated Claude Project. Sales managers query the Project for analysis. Great for pipeline reviews.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>3. HubSpot Workflows + webhook + Claude API.</strong> Trigger Claude on HubSpot events (new contact, deal stage change, form submission). Custom code (Zapier or custom function) calls Claude, returns content back to HubSpot. Practical 2-day build.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>4. Custom HubSpot integration via private app.</strong> Full read/write integration. Real engineering project but maximum control. Worth it for HubSpot-centric companies with specific workflow needs.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Where Claude beats HubSpot AI</span><h2 class="h2">Workflows where the external tool wins</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>Long-form content (blogs, emails over 200 words).</strong> Claude's output quality is significantly higher than HubSpot AI for sustained writing. Draft in Claude, paste into HubSpot for delivery.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Account research and brief generation.</strong> HubSpot AI doesn't do real research. Claude (especially paired with Perplexity for sources) does.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Sustained workflows across multiple sessions.</strong> HubSpot's in-platform AI is per-session. Claude Projects persist context across hundreds of sessions — much better for repeated workflows.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Coaching and analysis at the manager level.</strong> Pipeline reviews, deal coaching, forecasting commentary — HubSpot's AI is fine but Claude with a proper Project produces deeper analysis.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Where HubSpot AI is the right tool</span><h2 class="h2">Workflows where in-platform AI wins</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>Email send-time optimization and subject-line testing.</strong> HubSpot has the data; Claude doesn't.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Lead scoring and prediction.</strong> HubSpot's AI runs on your actual contact behavior. External Claude doesn't see this data.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>In-context email writing for individual sends.</strong> When a rep is in HubSpot writing a one-off email, opening Claude in another tab adds friction that often isn't worth the quality bump.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Quick summaries of contact activity or deal notes.</strong> HubSpot's summarizer is good enough for these glance-level tasks.</p>
    </div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Practical recommendation</span><h2 class="h2">The pattern most B2B HubSpot teams should adopt</h2>
    <p class="body">For a 5–25 person team on HubSpot: <strong>(1)</strong> use HubSpot's native AI for in-platform quick tasks (summaries, subject lines, individual email assists). <strong>(2)</strong> use Claude Team for everything sustained: long-form content, account briefs, pipeline analysis, coaching, board prep. <strong>(3)</strong> wire one or two high-frequency Claude→HubSpot automations via Zapier (e.g., new contact form submission triggers Claude to draft a personalized first-touch email back into HubSpot).</p>
    <p class="body">This pattern captures 90% of the value without significant engineering investment.</p>
    </div></section>

